15 section 4 of this bill, within 37 days after the later of the date on which the payment
16 becomes due under the grant agreement or the date on which the State entity that
17 made the grant receives a proper invoice, as defined in section 5 of this bill.
18 Section 8 of this bill provides that, with certain exceptions, a State grant-making
19 entity is liable for interest at a rate of 9 percent per annum on amounts which are
20 due and payable under a written grant agreement and which the State grant-making
21 entity has failed to submit for payment within 30 days after receipt of a proper
22 invoice. Section 8 provides that interest begins accruing on the 38th day after the
23 date on which the State grant-making entity receives a proper invoice and requires
24 interest to be paid from the operating budget of the State grant-making entity, not
25 including funds appropriated to fund a grant.
26 Section 9 of this bill requires a State grant-making entity to mark an invoice
27 with the date the invoice was received and review the invoice as soon as practicable
28 to determine whether the invoice is a proper invoice. Section 9 authorizes a State
29 grant-making entity to use media that produce tangible recordings of information to
30 expedite payment, rather than requiring original paper documents, but requires a
31 State grant-making entity to provide adequate safeguards and controls to ensure the
32 integrity of the data and to prevent duplicate processing.
THE PEOPLE OF THE STATE OF NEVADA, REPRESENTED IN
SENATE AND ASSEMBLY, DO ENACT AS FOLLOWS:
1 Section 1. Chapter 353 of NRS is hereby amended by adding
2 thereto the provisions set forth as sections 2 to 9, inclusive, of this
3 act.
4 Sec. 2. As used in sections 2 to 9, inclusive, of this act, unless
5 the context otherwise requires, the words and terms defined in
6 sections 3, 4 and 5 of this act have the meanings ascribed to them
7 in those sections.
8 Sec. 3. 1. “Grant” means a legal instrument of financial
9 assistance between a State grant-making entity and a nonprofit
10 organization exempt from taxation under section 501(c) of the
11 Internal Revenue Code, 26 U.S.C. § 501(c), that is:
12 (a) Used to enter into a relationship the principal purpose of
13 which is to transfer anything of value from the State grant-making
14 entity to the grant recipient to carry out a public purpose
15 authorized by law and not to acquire property or services for the
16 direct benefit or use of the State grant-making entity;
17 (b) Used to provide for one or more payments in
18 reimbursement for services or other performance under the
19 agreement on a scheduled or other incremental basis; and
20 (c) Distinguished from a cooperative agreement in that it does
21 not provide for substantial involvement between the State grant-
22 making entity and the grant recipient in carrying out the activity
23 contemplated by the award.
24 2. The term does not include an instrument that provides
25 only:
